title: For Sale/Trade:  Price Reduced! German Deutsche Werk Ortgies .32ACP W/Owner's Manual
postcontent:
Very good condition German made Ortgies 7.65mm (.32ACP). This gun is the commercial version, and the 6th variant (there were six model variants?). The Ortgies pocket pistols were made (officially) from 1919 to 1924. This particular gun (according to the serial number) was made around 1922-23. The Orgies semi-automatic pistols were excellent, well made guns. The design was ahead of its time. This gun has the factory original 7rd magazine. Overall, this gun is in very good condition. Has all matching numbers (barrel, frame, slide). Bluing is in really good condition for its age (this gun is at least 90 years old). All original finish, not re-blued, or anything like that. Has factory wood grips. The grips has no cracks, splits, or damages. Has a few minor dents and dings. Barrel is in very good condition - has a few minor surface rust. Bore is in very good condition. Has a a few minor rust (the Germans or people back in the old days used highly corrosive ammo). In addition, there's an old Ortgies owner's manual. It's really worn out, tattered, but all the pages are there (but not intact - it looks like as old as the gun itself).  You must be at least 21 years old or older and have a valid Kentucky driver's license (KY CCDW) to buy/trade this gun. Local (Kentucky) sale/trade only. No shipping. Just email me with any questions. Serious inquiries only please. Thanks for looking.

 -- Below is an excerpt from one of the Ortgies websites. It is not my own. I am just giving a credit to the author/creator of that particular website. You can do a google (or yahoo) search on this particular pistol on the internet. There are several Ortgies websites on line --

 " The Ortgies pistol has a number of unusual design features. The most obvious is its grip safety which, once squeezed, stays in the “fire” position without further pressure of the hand on the grip. A button on the left side of the gun allows the grip safety to pop back out. Since the grip safety is powered by the striker spring, the safety can only be popped out, i.e., placed in the “safe” position, when the striker is cocked. Hence, if the safety is enabled, the gun is cocked. When the grip safety is enabled, the sear is prevented from moving downward and the tension on the striker spring is reduced. Pressing the safety- enabling button also allows the slide to be lifted off the frame rail for disassembly. The striker serves as the ejector. "

postcontent:
I collected snub .38s for years, and this was the crown jewel of my collection, arguably THE finest .38 snub ever made.

This is a custom shop Speed Six with EVERY available option in near mint condition.  Was presented to NRA Director Jeanne E Bray in 1976 by the VP of Ruger, and I have a stack of documents proving authenticity as well as the original red box.  Never carried, probably never even fired by Ms Bray as she passed away shortly after receipt.  The dealer who purchased this from her state fired 6 rounds through it to test function and accuracy, and I fired 12 through it myself.  18 rounds total down the pipe.  Like New condition.

Options include: stainless steel, concealment grips, custom 2.5" barrel, bobbed and checkered hammer with no spur for DA/SA shooting, internals stoned and polished with trigger pull lightened.  All modifications done at Ruger custom hop.  SMOOTHEST, lightest DA trigger I've ever experienced.  All in a heavy duty revolver that can easily handle a constant diet of magnum strength +P+ Treasury loads.  I fired standard pressure FMJ through this and it was like shooting an airgun.  Zero recoil.   

Why am I selling the BEST snubnosed 38 ever made?  I could use the extra cash, and it is a bit heavier than I'm comfortably with.  Great for a nightstand, purse, belt holster, or shoulder holster, but certainly not a pocket gun.

Asking only $700 with box and paperwork.  Will not ship unless you're willing to pay 800 via USPS MO sent Priority Mail but I really do not want to ship.  Prefer to meet in or near Denver.  CASH ONLY.  Possible partial trades include: alloy P230, nickel M37, pre-lock 342, pre-lock 442 and that is it.  ZERO interest in any other trades.
